votes.evidence:
I independently re-traced the full chain.

WRITER (materializer.py): MaterializationRun.result is a JSONField (apps/workspaces/models.py:90). run_pipeline (materializer.py:96-508) is the only function that persists the COMPLETED result. Every persisted shape lacks a top-level "tables" key and a "table"+"rows_loaded" pair:
- COMPLETED path, lines 465-477: final_result = {"sources": source_results, "pipeline": pipeline.name, "transforms": transform_result}; update(...result=final_result)
- Source-failure path, line 366-369: run.result = {"pipeline": ..., "sources": ...}
- Cancel paths, lines 395-399, 440: {"cancelled", "pipeline", "sources"} / {"cancelled", "sources"}
- Pre-loop failure, line 422-426: {"pipeline", "sources", "error"}
- Checkpoint writer _persist_source_results, line 621-624: {"pipeline", "sources"}
The top-level rows_loaded (line 504) lives ONLY in the function RETURN value (result dict at 498-505), which is never persisted to run.result. A repo-wide grep for any writer of result["tables"] or result["table"]+rows_loaded across mcp_server/ and apps/ (excluding tests) found none; server.py:481 only adds {"cancelled": True} onto the existing shape.

READER (server.py): get_schema_status single-tenant branch (689-735) loads last_run.result into result_data (718), then: `if "tables" in result_data:` (719) — false for every persisted shape — `elif "table" in result_data and "rows_loaded" in result_data:` (721) — also false (rows_loaded is never top-level in the persisted dict). So tables stays [] (initialized 714), and the response is {exists: True, state: ts.state (active), last_materialized_at: <set>, tables: []} (726-735). Confirmed: a fully successful single-tenant materialization yields tables=[].

DIVERGENCE with list_tables: list_tables (108-173) does NOT read run.result for the table list; it calls pipeline_list_tables (161) which reconciles against information_schema, returning the real tables. So in the same conversation list_tables returns populated tables while get_schema_status returns []. The disagreement is real.

REACHABILITY: get_schema_status is in MCP_TOOL_NAMES (apps/agents/graph/base.py:72) and registered via @mcp.tool() (server.py:651), so it is a live, agent-callable tool today. Mitigation is genuine but partial: the prompt pre-fetches schema context (base.py:757 comment "no need to call get_schema_status at runtime") and base_system.py (118,138,167) steers the agent to list_tables/describe_table. Nothing prevents the agent from calling get_schema_status and receiving tables=[].

File/line refs in the finding are accurate (server.py:689-735,718-724; materializer.py:366-504).
